 around the imminent 200th anniversary of the publication of »Des Knaben Wunderhorn« in 2006. For Heidelberg romanticism and for Volkspoesie in general, issues concerned with performance, the relationship between the oral and the written, citation, and intertextuality have always been central concerns. Alongside other works by Arnim and the Heidelberg romantics discussed here, Arnim and Brentano's »Des Knaben Wunderhorn« is an especially grateful subject for the discussion of these issues. Goethe himself stressed the performative aspect: »By right, this little book should be found in every house where fresh-minded people live, on the window-sill, under the mirror, or wherever hymn-books and cook-books normally lie, to be opened whenever the mood (good or bad) should take us, and we are in search of something like-minded or stimulating.«  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aRomanticismzGermanyzHeidelbergvCongresses. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh1 aBarth, Johannes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBorchmeyer, Dieter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeilchenfeldt, Konrad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGardiner, Ann Τ., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHäntzschel, Günter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHölter, Achim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJapp, Uwe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnaack, Jürgen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKremer, Detlef, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin, Dieter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relator